NEXT STEPS IN REOPENING THE ECONOMY

The new normal:

Via The Hill's Brett Samuels, Morgan Chalfant and Reid Wilson, President Trump unveiled a three-phase plan yesterday to reopen parts of the U.S. economy, but is allowing governors to use those guidelines to make their own decisions. https://bit.ly/3anupRf

The gist of the plan: It recommends that states see a reduction in coronavirus cases and flu-like symptoms before starting to ease restrictions. This ensures hospitals will be able to treat all patients without crisis care.

Keep in mind: A robust COVID-19 testing system is necessary for this plan.

Read the full 18-page plan from the White House: https://bit.ly/3esnrxn

BREAKDOWN OF THE THREE PHASES:

Phase One: "The first phase largely urges existing measures to remain in place while allowing certain businesses, such as gyms, to reopen if social distancing is possible."

Phase Two: "The second phase makes recommendations for states and regions with no evidence of a rebound of COVID-19 and that have twice satisfied the initial criteria on cases, hospitals and testing. It urges all vulnerable individuals to shelter in place and encourages others to exercise social distancing in public. In this phase, officials also say that nonessential travel can resume, schools can reopen, and large venues, gyms and bars can operate with social distancing steps in place. Officials recommend that businesses continue to encourage telework when possible and to close common areas where staff may congregate."

Phase Three: "The third phase, which is recommended only for states that have shown no signs of a spike in cases after restrictions are lifted and have satisfied the initial criteria a third time, allows public interactions and visits to nursing homes to resume and lets bars and restaurants expand their capacity. The third phase still encourages individuals to socially distance when possible and limit their time in large gatherings, while allowing employers to resume unrestricted staffing in the workplace."

REACTION FROM SENATE MINORITY LEADER CHARLES SCHUMER (D-N.Y.):

Schumer said on MSNBC's "Morning Joe": "The plan is a little more measured than what the president said in the past, which is good but there's a key thing missing in all this ... If we don't have a strong, adequate testing regime, we're going to have real trouble," he added. "You have to know who has the illness, who's immune from the illness and who could get the illness before we can determine who can go back to work and who can't." https://bit.ly/2VjgJlY

